        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Challenges ahead </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-18-2.png" alt="Challenges ahead " href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The recent <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/syria-assad-fall-rebels-hts-what-now-rcna183401" target="_blank">fall</a> of Bashar al-Assad’s regime in Syria has given hope for the return of displaced citizens after over a decade of civil war. The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) <a href="https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20241217-un-says-one-million-syrians-may-return-in-first-half-of-2025" target="_blank">estimates</a> that around one million Syrians may return during the first half of 2025 as the collapse of Assad’s government brings newfound optimism for resolution. However, the agency warns that despite this political shift, the humanitarian crisis persists, and rebuilding the country will pose immense challenges.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">While some Syrians are eager to go home, the UN emphasizes that no one should be forced to return prematurely. Many areas remain devastated, and safety cannot yet be guaranteed. Many refugees have built so much in the countries they fled to. Many obtained education, opened businesses and became citizens. Host countries are urged to maintain asylum rights and avoid hasty deportations. This moment marks a turning point, but careful planning and ongoing support will be critical for lasting stability.​</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
