          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Assad remarks </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Bashar al-Assad made his first public comments since the rebels <a href="https://apnews.com/article/syria-war-assad-russia-news-16-december-2024-72a8e44f762da2ff78434ff76faeb633" target="_blank">captured</a> Damascus, which led to his departure. He claimed he had no intention of stepping down and wanted to continue fighting. However, Russia evacuated him to their Hmeimim airbase and later to Moscow after the base came under drone attack. He made <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/syria-updates-assad-makes-first-statement-since-ousting/live-71064989" target="_blank">remarks</a> about the “state falling into the hands of terrorism” and a “void of purpose” position of Assad, giving us an image of an unwilling figurehead rather than a leader ousted under pressure, as widely speculated. However, the residents of Damascus believe that Assad had abandoned the state long ago.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Russian announcements of his evacuation, arrival, and asylum in Russia signal a shift in Syria’s power dynamics. It raises questions about Russia’s next steps in managing its interests in Syria without Assad, as well as the long-term future of the Syrian regime. Russia has said at the moment, it plans to <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/12/16/politics/russia-military-syria-withdrawal/index.html" target="_blank">step back</a> from Syria but not away entirely.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

