          Bolivian prosecutors have issued an <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/bolivian-prosecutors-seek-arrest-warrant-for-evo-morales/a-71075441" target="_blank">arrest warrant</a> for former President Evo Morales as part of an investigation into accusations of statutory rape involving a minor. The 65-year-old is accused of "trafficking" a 15-year-old girl during his presidency from 2006 to 2019 and allegedly fathering a child with her in 2016. This is the second warrant in the case; an appeal from his lawyers blocked the first. Morales has denied any wrongdoing and claims his successor, Luis Arce, is trying to prevent him from running in next year's election. He has remained in the rural Chapare region with loyal supporters since September.</p>
